{
  "card_id": "london_reversal",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "London Reversal",
  "aliases": [
    "2 a.m. reversal",
    "4-hour c2 closure",
    "4-hour C2 closure",
    "Bearish Classic Expansion",
    "bearish classic expansion",
    "Bullish Classic Expansion",
    "bullish classic expansion",
    "classic expansion candle",
    "Classic Expansion Candle",
    "london reversal new york continuation",
    "London Reversal New York Continuation",
    "london reversal profile",
    "London Reversal Profile",
    "伦敦反转"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A daily profile where the London session (02:00–05:00 ET) sweeps a higher time frame level or liquidity, then reverses via a Change in the State of Delivery (CISD/MSS), forming the daily candle's wick. The New York session continues in the reversal direction, completing the daily OHLC as bullish (Open-Low-High-Close) or bearish (Open-High-Low-Close).",
  "identification_rules": [
    "During the London Kill Zone (02:00–05:00 ET), price sweeps a liquidity level (swing high/low) or reaches a higher-time-frame PD Array.",
    "A Change in the State of Delivery (CISD) is confirmed by price closing through a series of same-direction candles (e.g., closes above a series of down-close candles for bullish, or below a series of up-close candles for bearish) on the 15-minute or 30-minute chart.",
    "A 4-hour candle 2 closure often occurs, sweeping the prior candle's extreme and closing back inside its range, confirming the reversal.",
    "The reversal is ideally confirmed by a cracking correlation SMT against a correlated asset.",
    "The London move forms the wick of the daily candle; the body and close are not yet established during London.",
    "During the New York session (08:30–12:00 ET), price continues in the direction of London's reversal rather than extending London's initial sweep direction.",
    "Key New York time levels (08:30, 09:30, 10:00) are monitored for manipulation runs or continuation entries aligned with the London reversal direction.",
    "The daily candle closes in the direction of the New York continuation, completing the Open-Low-High-Close (bullish) or Open-High-Low-Close (bearish) structure.",
    "For bullish reversal: open → downward expansion (lower wick) → close above open. For bearish reversal: open → upward expansion (upper wick) → close below open.",
    "Price must have touched a higher time frame key level or PD Array during the London session (distinguishing from New York Reversal, where the touch occurs later)."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Once London confirms a CISD/MSS, traders wait for New York session (08:30-12:00 ET) to enter in the reversal direction. Entry on retest of the order block formed by the CISD candle, with stop beyond the London sweep extreme. Minimum target 2R; extended targets include previous day high/low, opposing daily range extreme, fair value gaps, or daily equilibrium. New York manipulation moves at 08:30 or 09:30 against the reversal direction are entry opportunities, not invalidations.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Entering during London session before CISD/MSS confirmation, risking being caught in the manipulation sweep.",
    "Misidentifying the profile when New York does not immediately continue in the reversal direction at 08:30 — an opposing manipulation move is normal and should be used as entry.",
    "Failing to wait for a close beyond the series of same-direction candles before marking the order block.",
    "Confusing London Reversal with New York Reversal when London's move does not touch a HTF key level.",
    "Confusing the reversal direction, leading to wrong New York continuation expectation.",
    "Ignoring New York 08:30 news manipulation, misjudging it as real continuation.",
    "Targeting an intermediate low/high when the actual HTF draw on liquidity is further away.",
    "Taking the reversal without confirming with SMT/cracking correlation and precision swing point.",
    "Misreading shallow moves against the trend as reversals; these are often retracements supporting continuation."
  ],
